pm/restify-monitor`\n\n## Usage\n\nTo install: `npm install --save @npm/restify-monitor`.\n\n```javascript\nvar restify = require('restify');\nvar monitor = require('@npm/restify-monitor');\n\nvar server = restify.createServer();\nmonitor(server,\n{\n    logger: bole('my-little-pony'),\n    metrics: 'tcp://localhost:3333'\n});\n```\n\nWhat it does: Adds a logging `after` handler to the restify server. If you provide a `logger` field in the options object, it'll decorate each request with the given logger.\n\nIt will honor a metrics collector URI passed in a a string in the options `metrics` field. If you do not pass that option, it will look for the environment variable `METRICS`. *It will silently discard* any pre-constructed metrics emitter object passed in the options field. This is to prevent you from trying to use an ancient emitter object from enterprise-configurator.\n\nThe monitor also adds GET and HEAD routes for two monitoring endpoints.\n\n`GET /_monitor/ping`: responds with 200 pong.\n\n`GET /_monitor/status`: responds with a status object containing the following data:\n\n* name: the server name you provided to restify\n* pid: process.pid\n* uptime: process.uptime()\n* rss: process.memoryUsage()\n* git: hash of the head commit if the process is running in a git repo\n* message: commit message of the head commit if the process is in a git repo\n\n## License\n\nISC.\n","maintainers":[{"name":"mmalecki","email":"me@mmalecki.com"}],"time":{"modified":"2017-04-12T19:00:25.318Z","created":"2015-11-18T13:07:52.691Z","0.1.9":"2015-11-18T13:07:52.691Z","1.0.0":"2015-11-25T01:13:27.242Z","1.0.1":"2015-12-01T00:07:57.215Z","1.0.2":"2015-12-31T01:30:01.553Z","1.0.3":"2016-01-06T22:12:15.173Z","1.1.0":"2016-01-21T20:30:21.006Z","1.1.1":"2016-01-22T22:57:33.667Z","1.2.0":"2016-03-21T21:50:04.487Z","1.2.1":"2016-04-06T17:24:47.868Z","1.3.0":"2016-10-07T21:28:14.625Z","1.3.1":"2017-04-12T19:00:25.318Z"},"homepage":"https://github.com/npm/restify-monitor","repository":{